english:
  title: Preface to the Pulse Diagnosis Illustrated
  author: Lee Sung-in
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Medical texts are not easy to read, nor is the art of medicine simple to master—this conviction I have held for long. Among physicians of our time, there are those who cannot even properly parse the sentences of medical writings, yet claim, "I have perfected the medical art." I have despised such charlatans for many years.

    Our nation has established ten schools of learning to cultivate talent, with medicine being one among them. The Superintendent of Studies, Jeong Ye-mun of the Three Peaks, declared: "A physician must discern the pulse without error; only then will prescriptions prove effective." Having examined the theories of the ancients, he created diagrams to clarify their principles, composed formulae to capture their subtleties, and titled this work "Pulse Diagnosis Illustrated." He commanded that I add my commentary below.

    Though my studies of medicine are considerable, this book achieves a rare balance—detailed without excess, concise without omission. Those who study it carefully will surely discover the vital essence within its pages. Yet whether one goes on to read all texts and master all techniques depends upon the individual themselves. So I urge: persevere, persevere!
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The "Three Peaks" (三峯) refers to Jeong Do-jeon (鄭道傳), a prominent Neo-Confucian scholar and administrator of the early Joseon period.
  - key: ''
    value: The ten schools of learning (十學科) established by the early Joseon government included medicine as an important field of study alongside classical studies, law, and other disciplines.
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase "vital essence" (肯綮) is an idiom referring to the crucial point or crux of a matter, derived from the anatomical knowledge of cutting between joints without resistance.
